03911nam a22004335i 9781503619227DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222000cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815036192277 a10.1515/97815036192272doi  a(DE-B1597)582354  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aSOC0520002bisacsh1 aLuhmann, Niklas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Reality of the Mass Media /cNiklas Luhmann. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (160 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCultural Memory in the Present00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- t1. Differentiation as a Doubling of Reality -- t2. Self-reference and Other reference -- t3. Coding -- t4. System-specific Universalism -- t5. News and In-depth Reporting -- t6. Ricúpero -- t7. Advertising -- t8. Entertainment -- t9. Unity and Structural Couplings -- t10. Individuals -- t11. The Construction of Reality -- t12. The Reality of Construction -- t13. The Function of the Mass Media -- t14. The Public -- t15. Schema Formation -- t16. Second-order Cybernetics as Paradox -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn The Reality of the Mass Media, Luhmann extends his theory of social systems—applied in his earlier works to the economy, the political system, art, religion, the sciences, and law—to an examination of the role of mass media in the construction of social reality. Luhmann argues that the system of mass media is a set of recursive, self-referential programs of communication, whose functions are not determined by the external values of truthfulness, objectivity, or knowledge, nor by specific social interests or political directives. Rather, he contends that the system of mass media is regulated by the internal code information/noninformation, which enables the system to select its information (news) from its own environment and to communicate this information in accordance with its own reflexive criteria. Despite its self-referential quality, Luhmann describes the mass media as one of the key cognitive systems of modern society, by means of which society constructs the illusion of its own reality. The reality of mass media, he argues, allows societies to process information without destabilizing social roles or overburdening social actors. It forms a broad reservoir (memory) of options for the future coordination of action, and it provides parameters for the stabilization of political reproduction of society, as it produces a continuous self-description of the world around which modern society can orient itself. In his discussion of mass media, Luhmann elaborates a theory of communication in which communication is seen not as the act of a particular consciousness, nor the medium of integrative social norms, but merely the technical codes through which systemic operations arrange and perpetuate themselves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150361922740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503619227423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503619227/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles